xxl.core.predicates
Class Equal<P>

java.lang.Object
  xxl.core.predicates.Predicate<P>

Type Parameters:
P - the type of the predicate's parameters.
All Implemented Interfaces:
Serializable
public class Equal<P>
extends Predicate<P>

This class provides a binary predicate that determines whether two given arguments are equal. The invoke method of the predicate is based on the equals method of the class Object.

See Also:

Field Detail

DEFAULT_INSTANCE

public static final Equal<Object> DEFAULT_INSTANCE
This instance can be used for getting a default instance of Equal. It is similar to the Singleton Design Pattern (for further details see Creational Patterns, Prototype in Design Patterns: Elements of Reusable Object-Oriented Software by Erich Gamma, Richard Helm, Ralph Johnson, and John Vlissides) except that there are no mechanisms to avoid the creation of other instances of Equal.

Method Detail

invoke

public boolean invoke(P argument0,
                      P argument1)
Returns whether the given arguments are equal or not. If a null value is allowed to be passed as argument, the user has to wrap this predicate by calling Predicates.newNullSensitiveEqual(boolean). The exact implementation of this method is 
        return argument0.equals(argument1);

Overrides:
invoke in class Predicate<P>
Parameters:
argument0 - the first argument to the predicate.
argument1 - the second argument to the predicate.
Returns:
true if the given arguments are equal, otherwise false.
